headline: Democratic presidential candidates squabble over key issues at debate

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hi, I'm Greg Gutfeld with Emily Compagno, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and her bean bag chair is an actual beanbag, Dana Perino -- "The Five." Well, that was a little weird affair last night. It was less of a debate and more of awkward family squabble done in front of all the neighbors.

utterances.speaker: JOHN HICKENLOOPER
utterances.sentences: I think if we're going to force Americans to make these radical changes, they're not going to go along. Throw your hands up. But you haven't --

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN
utterances.sentences: It was also mention in this.

utterances.speaker: JAKE TAPPER
utterances.sentences: We're going to come to you in one second.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS
utterances.sentences: Every credible poll that I have seen has me beating Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: TIM RYAN
utterances.sentences: Hillary Clinton was winning in the polls, too.

utterances.speaker: TAPPER
utterances.sentences: Who is offering a false choice here?

utterances.speaker: BETO O'ROURKE
utterances.sentences: You have some.

utterances.speaker: JOHN DELANEY
utterances.sentences: I think Democrats win when we run on real solutions, not on impossible promises. When we run on things that are workable, not fairy tale economics.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: I don't understand why anybody does to all the trouble of running for President of the United States just to talk about what we really can't do and shouldn't fight for.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Guys, guys, guys, let's bring the group counselling inside. It's making the kids and dogs uncomfortable. Thank God there was a therapist on hand to make things better or worse.

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON
utterances.sentences: What do you say to those Trump voters who prioritize the economy over the president's bigotry?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, no bias there. So what do you say to half the country who are racists? No wonder CNN is bleeding viewers. Next time, leave the hard news to Jake and Bash. But much of the debate came down to a three-part episode. First, a left-wing candidate explains how to make everything free. Second, someone smarter points out how you can't make everything free. Third, someone shouts, but evil Trump. Thank God, Ms. Cleo showed up.

utterances.speaker: MARIANNE WILLIAMSON
utterances.sentences: If you think any of this wonkiness is going to deal with this dark psychic force of the collective eyes hatred that this president is bringing up in this country, then I'm afraid that the Democrats are going to see some very dark days.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Love her or hate her, she's got two things in common with Trump.  She's no politician and she's got a point of view. Just don't ask her about her pet.   UNIDENTIFIED REPORTER Do you have a pet?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMSON
utterances.sentences: Do I have a pet? I have a cat, and the cat died.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The cat died. That ain't no politician's answer. But she wasn't the only one with Trump on the brain.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: RYAN
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: STEVE BULLOCK
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS
utterances.sentences: Trump is a pathological liar.

utterances.speaker: O'ROURKE
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: AMY KLOBUCHAR
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: HICKENLOOPER
utterances.sentences: That's how we're going to beat Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: BULLOCK
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMSON
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump disgraces the office of president.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMSON
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: HICKENLOOPER
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: RYAN
utterances.sentences: We've got to get rid of Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: O'ROURKE
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: DELANEY
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump is the symptom of a disease.

utterances.speaker: BUTTIGIEG
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: KLOBUCHAR
utterances.sentences: Let's get real. Tonight, we debate but ultimately we have to beat Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know, maybe it's me but all that talk about Trump makes him even more alluring. It's like when dad says stay away from those magazines at the barber shop. You think, hey, let's go check out those magazines at the barber shop. Juan laughed at that. It's weird how ten people talking trash about you makes you seem so much bigger.  Yet, Trump loomed over the debate like the devil in the exorcist. Reducing the party to a bunch of possess children helplessly shaking in their beds.  No comfort came from that room, but also no candidate either. Dana, I saw one of your perceptive tweets last night, and you do that thing where you -- I notice not only what was there but what wasn't there. And what wasn't there -- what wasn't mention, Dana?

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, first of all, CNN, I praise them for starting the debate at 8 PM, but what wasn't there was the truth that it was three hours long --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- not two hours long. I don't know --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You see there's no mention of impeachment, and no Mueller, no collusion.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah. And also, no send her back.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Send her back was a big -- and no Biden.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No Biden.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Like, nobody mentioned any of those things. That, obviously, is not going to be the case tonight when Biden is on the stage. The other thing that you mentioned that Marianne has that Trump had, she also has a following.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: A ready-made following. They've been following her for decades.  It's not the same crowd that followed President Trump through -- if you followed him in New York when he was on The Apprentice who became an international star. Marianne is an international star as well.  So I think she's confounding Democrats a little bit because -- like, why does she have all this support? Where is it coming from? She's been building it for years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I also like -- I do like the fact that I understand what she's saying. She's waging a psychological battle, Juan. Like, she's talking about the psyche of the nation, and I think people can understand that.  What did you make of like the family feud last night between the moderates and the not moderates?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: First, you know, I listened to your monologue with such interest, and then I heard about Ms. Cleo.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And I thought to myself, isn't that -- she was the -- was she a black woman on TV?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She was psychic. Wasn't she Ms. Cleo the psychic? The 1-800 number.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, that was it. You could dial 1-800.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, yes, yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So now, 1-800 you get Marianne.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You get Marianne and -- but I don't know if she gets the White House. But I must say she got lots of attention. I read -- and because this is so alien to me. I read she was the most searched person on the stage last night in terms of googling and the like, right? So I guess people are like, oh, who is she? What's this about?  I think some of you know who she is. I really don't know who she is because, politically, she's a nobody. So it's a little-bit of a stunner.  I get the whole Trump analogy (INAUDIBLE) like Trump. But, you know what, at some point, I think, would she fall off the stage for the next round?  Apparently not.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, I think she might gone up --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: She has a following.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Was there anybody like -- you thought -- out of the group that you thought was the strongest?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I think, clearly, Elizabeth Warren came on the stage as the strongest and left as the strongest. I don't think anybody did any damage to Elizabeth Warren. To me, the whole notion that it's a family feud I think it's healthy. I think that's what we should be seeing. We should be seeing a debate that helps to determine who the candidate. I mean, you look back to 2016. Republicans were far more divided. Lying Ted, Little Marco, low-energy. You think about the wall. There was only one guy up there who said, yeah, the wall is a great idea. Trade, foreign trade, non-intervention -- war in Iraq. Donald Trump didn't tell the truth, but he said that he had opposed the war in Iraq or something.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He kind of did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Directionally told the truth.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know, but I thought that it was a real substantive debate about Medicare for all, about the environment with Delaney playing the foil to Sanders and Warren, making some real good points and forcing them to defend their points. And then when he spoke about the costs --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: We'll do that in the B-block.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK. Let's do it in --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: B-block. All right, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: You called it a squabble. You called it a feud. I say that it was an intervention. This was the rise of the realist who are trying to rescue the party away from socialism. And Bernie and Warren, they're just lighting themselves on fire right now. This is a big bonfire of socialism. And all these realist were like throwing water -- hey, math, reality, this is going to get us killed in a landslide. But they don't care. They just want to light everything on fire and so the audience. And the audience claps every time some socialist says something crazy --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know why? Because it's popular.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It is -- socialism is popular --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So were cults too in the 70's, Juan. I'm not saying this is going to work. Something popular doesn't mean it's going to be good. But, right now, I think what's happening is, Warren, I disagree. I thought she was frenetic. I thought she was annoying.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Really?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She failed the commander-in-chief test when she took the first nuke strike option off the table. Like she's going to sacrifice an American city and let North Korea throw a missile over here, and then respond after we lost millions of people. Absolutely crazy. She refused to answer the question about whether she'd raise taxes on the middle class.  And then Bernie gets out there. Bernie is a nothing in Washington his whole career. He only knows how to take. He doesn't know how to create.  And he's just a rage-a-holic. No one was presidential timber. No one had any sense of humor. Marianne Williamson, she's like homeopathic therapy. Everyone's on stage is like Advil and aspirin and bare, and she's like yoga, like CBD oil, and she's -- but she's tapped into some real energy in the country. I just don't think that energy is fully formed yet, but she's got into it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What about you, Emily? What did you -- what were your highlights and low lights?

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Yeah. It's interesting, I agree with part of what you said. To me, it was like a Hunger Games style big fish in a small pond. And the progressives won to me. I think Bernie emerged as the commander, and that he and Elizabeth were clearly the pros on stage, but they failed at that commander level, I agree. I think, to me, it was clear that the progressives won. But at what cost to the party, at what cost to the reality of the moderate faction, which to me was eclipsed. I think that the a-ha moments, and the dramatic moments, and the zingers and quips got all the applause and got all the excitement. But in reality, I think a lot of voters at home were like, wait, I would like, actually, more info from that moderate over there, and I would like more air time from that moderate over there. And so, to me, it was analogy of, once again, CNN taking away the choice from the voter at home --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You couldn't really get full answers because the rules that they had set out had the moderators were forced then to try to -- to cut off everybody just as they were about to make a point --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- they'll cut them off.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah. I thought two-thirds of the moderators did a really good job. I thought that they must have been cringing with Lemon going -- just editorializing, I thought it was a bit odd. I mean, it's like having me up there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's what Trump said. So Trump went after Lemon, right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And I mean, you know, he's in self-defense mode. But, you know, to me there were two outstanding moments for the Democrats. One, when Elizabeth Warren says to the so-called moderates, I think they're more conservative, hey, why are you running for president just to tell us what we can't do? The other one was Pete -- Mayor Pete saying, oh, you know what? The Republicans are going to call us socialist whether you are liberal or conservative.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Typical socialist.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: They're called conservatives now, but the ground has shifted under their feet --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- it's like because the party has moved so far-left, then you ended up -- you end up being called a conservative Democrat.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Did you see who the most tweeted about candidate was, though, by the way. It was still Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: No matter what happened, it was still Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: There you go. All right, we've got to move on. We've got another segment. The gloves come off with socialists battling moderates for Medicare for all.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Second of all -- second of all --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I wrote the damn bill.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: More of the heated debate moments, next.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Peter chose that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I don't know? Peter chose it. OK. The fireworks in Detroit as the debate brawl breaks out over Medicare for all. Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren attacking private health insurance while clashing with moderates over how to pay for their progressive plans. Now, both Warren and Sanders forced to defend their policies last night, watch.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: He has called the idea a political suicide that will just get President Trump re-elected. What do you say to Congressman Delaney?

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (D-VT)
utterances.sentences: You're wrong.

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.sentences: When you end up in a hospital in Canada, you come out with no bill at all. Healthcare is a human right, not a privilege. I believe that. I will fight for that.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: But we don't have to go around and be the party of subtraction and telling half the country who has private health insurance that their health insurance is illegal. But why do we got to be the party of taking something away from people.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: No is the party --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: That's what they're running on. They're running on telling half the country that your health insurance is illegal.

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN (D-MA)
utterances.sentences: We are not about trying to take away healthcare from anyone. That's what the Republicans are trying to do. And we should stop using Republican talking points in order to talk with each other about how to best provide that healthcare.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Republican arguments aren't necessarily just talking points, Jesse. But that got pretty heated.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sometimes they're just points.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes, the arguments.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: How are you going to pay for it? Are you going to raise taxes?  And how is it going to work? Apparently, that's a partisan talking point.  If Obamacare was so great, why is everyone talking about repealing and replacing Obamacare on a Democrat debate? I mean, this is crazy. I couldn't even understand half of their plans. They don't make any sense at all. Tim Ryan made the best point I think of everybody. These unions have negotiated these amazing healthcare plan, Cadillac plans they're so good.  They have their own name. Why would you rip those away? And not only that, and then give them to illegal immigrants? It makes no sense politically and as a policy, and Warren totally out of touch. I don't know about you guys, but I like my healthcare. I go to the doctor. I check in.  I give a $5 co-pay. He tells me I'm fine. I leave. I do no paperwork.  It's great. And 180 million Americans feel that way. Only 27 million Americans do not have health insurance right now. Let's focus on them instead of tearing the whole system down. And Bernie, he thinks making a profit is evil. I don't know what he's talking about.  So many great things have been done through Aetna, Blue Cross and Blue Shield. I don't think these are evil companies. I think these are good companies that need to bring costs down. And there's ways to do that without destroying a great system. Trump can exploit this divide within the Democratic Party, and it's a gift because the Republicans -- I'm not really sure what their healthcare plan is, but the Democrats are making it so easy to exploit by offering up this socialist utopia that makes no sense and does remove healthcare from a lot of people.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And it felt like, Emily, that Delaney and others were trying to say, look, we know from the researcher out in the field, they're talking to people, you say Medicare for all, kind of popular. As soon as you start saying here's what could happen under it. And that's why I like Bernie Sanders is almost impervious to the consequences of the bill -- the damn bill that he wrote, right? So he's like -- he say I wrote the bill, like, yeah, there are consequence -- you can't say it's free.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Exactly. And I think that's why the momentum behind it stops at the tag line, right? It stops at Medicare for all, and then once you get into the iceberg below it, it's so obvious that as the cost came out today, the $3.2 trillion, it's not worth it. It takes away choice from people.  It ignores the fact that everything has a cost and somewhere it has to be absorbed. So if it's not you absorbing it, then it's a business absorbing it which means that you're fielding the cost later, etcetera. So once -- again, I think it's just that kind of overarching approach that they're taking. And I think it was funny that immediately Bernie's camp would made the sticker, I wrote the damn bill, and he thought it was so amazing. And I think the GOP should make stickers that say 3.2 trillion --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's 32 trillion.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: It's 32 trillion, thank you. Even more as rebuttal. Exactly.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Healthcare we know, Juan, like one of the top issues. People worry -- and mostly about the cost of like hospital care, or unexpected expenses that they are worried would bankrupt them. So you think the Democrats have a plan for that, that's better than Republicans?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, because I think in action is not acceptable, Dana. And the Republicans have no plan. Remember, you had two years with Republicans in control of the House and the Senate and the White House and they did nothing. Jesse is talking about, oh, people don't like Obamacare. The polls show people now more than 50 percent like Obamacare. And guess what?  The Democrats are trying to build on Obamacare. It's only Biden who says he would just stick with Obamacare and built slightly repair its flaws.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: People like their own companies-sponsored health insurance.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, they do. But the key point to me is --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So why do they want to take that away?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: They don't want to take it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes, they do. That's the Medicare for all plan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Medicare for all would say that you actually get fewer deductions --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- Fox News sponsored health insurance policy --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Excuse me, let me finish.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- be given to the feds?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm not giving anything.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They manage the whole plan, Juan. It's a government-run plan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And I'm saying I would get more coverage. My taxes would go up.  That's the thing that people are pointing to. And also the argument --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK. Here's what I'm thinking to you. Taxes might go up. And secondly, people would say it's a big government plan. Do you really trust big government to deliver for the individual? And on both cases what you hear from Sanders and Warren is, yeah, your taxes might go up, but you would pay less for coverage and all those people --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All those people who have less than adequate coverage would be covered.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Even just looking at the U.K., it's never enough.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: When the Democrats say taxes might go up, that means taxes are going up. OK. I always figure like let's do this to what the left really likes. Like education, the campus. We know Medicare for all will result in doctors being paid less. Hospitals being paid less. Procedures being paid less. Long waiting lines to see specialists and more pressure on a system especially primary care. So let's apply this. Let's do education for all. Not cancelling the debt because that only hurts the banks. But let's say free education for all. That would apply to professors, right?  The left. They would have longer hours, they would have lower pay, they'll have more red tape, and there'd be no funding for all of their precious research because there wouldn't be any money. So if you applied Medicare for all into an area where you can't demonize the person like a doctor, but like, oh, the poor professors, they would run screaming. They'd have their pitchforks if they knew where they could buy them at the hardware store.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So you know what that's called? Public schools. Public schools work.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I'm talking about universities.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, I'm just saying, that's what we know.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Actually, I love that. I think we should come back to it another day. But for now, Democrat candidates clash over -- guess what? Climate change and a green new deal, of course. The fiery showdown, but we heard it before when we return.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It wouldn't be a Democratic debate without liberal doomsday climate predictions and the green new deal. The candidates rolled out their tired talking points and there was also one big moment everyone is talking about. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Climate crisis is the existential crisis for our world. It puts every living thing on this planet at risk.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: We don't have more than ten years to get this right.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: By 2030, we will have passed the point of no return on climate.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: There is no choice. We have got to be super aggressive.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The green new deal makes sure that every Americans guaranteed a government job if they want. That is a disaster at the ballot box. You might as well FedEx the election to Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right. Dana, first of all, I thought it was 12 years was the time limit when we had to survive -- I don't know what happened?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: In 1997, when I first worked on the hill, and there was a hearing about this, it was 30 years -- so 12. I think by tonight's debate, it will be five weeks.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Because they have to keep ratcheting it up, up and up.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And I think Al Gore said that in 2014 the earth was going to be decimated. And now it's 2019.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: 2019. Well, here we are. And I think that they've done to themselves a very good service of -- it's hard to do it in a sound bite, OK? To say the world is ending. We've just seen all of these huge fires in the arctic, right? The tundra is melting and the things are happening - - like, it's all happening -- like, they could say it's happening right now. The question is, then what do you do about it? How do you act on it? And Hickenlooper, the governor of Colorado, is basically trying to say you have to be realistic about this. You're talking about adaptation and how much it's going to cost, et cetera. Instead, I feel like the Democrats when they talk about climate change, it's literally the same discussion every time.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right. And one of those things, Greg, is guaranteed income. And if you don't have a job, guaranteed wages, guaranteed healthcare, guaranteed housing, everything is free.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: They have the end but they don't have the means. The problem is it's really easy to propose these giant fantasies that it is to expose the brutal folly behind it because everybody tunes out. That's why you have to have an adult in the room that says hold on. Let's explain how we get there. We're not going to be taxing the rich. We're going to be taxing everybody 70 grand, and that's when the American people will be laughing at the green new deal, laughing at it, the original lyric in our country music song. The problem is people don't like boring stuff. And boring stuff works, marriage, budgets, process, laws, all boring. But apocalyptic predictions are exciting and people eat them up and it's sad. Sad, I say.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Hi, I'm Greg Gutfeld with Emily Compagno, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and her bean bag chair is an actual beanbag, Dana Perino -- "The Five." Well, that was a little weird affair last night. It was less of a debate and more of awkward family squabble done in front of all the neighbors.

utterances.speaker: JOHN HICKENLOOPER
utterances.utterance: I think if we're going to force Americans to make these radical changes, they're not going to go along. Throw your hands up. But you haven't --

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN
utterances.utterance: It was also mention in this.

utterances.speaker: JAKE TAPPER
utterances.utterance: We're going to come to you in one second.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS
utterances.utterance: Every credible poll that I have seen has me beating Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: TIM RYAN
utterances.utterance: Hillary Clinton was winning in the polls, too.

utterances.speaker: TAPPER
utterances.utterance: Who is offering a false choice here?

utterances.speaker: BETO O'ROURKE
utterances.utterance: You have some.

utterances.speaker: JOHN DELANEY
utterances.utterance: I think Democrats win when we run on real solutions, not on impossible promises. When we run on things that are workable, not fairy tale economics.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.utterance: I don't understand why anybody does to all the trouble of running for President of the United States just to talk about what we really can't do and shouldn't fight for.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Guys, guys, guys, let's bring the group counselling inside. It's making the kids and dogs uncomfortable. Thank God there was a therapist on hand to make things better or worse.

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON
utterances.utterance: What do you say to those Trump voters who prioritize the economy over the president's bigotry?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, no bias there. So what do you say to half the country who are racists? No wonder CNN is bleeding viewers. Next time, leave the hard news to Jake and Bash. But much of the debate came down to a three-part episode. First, a left-wing candidate explains how to make everything free. Second, someone smarter points out how you can't make everything free. Third, someone shouts, but evil Trump. Thank God, Ms. Cleo showed up.

utterances.speaker: MARIANNE WILLIAMSON
utterances.utterance: If you think any of this wonkiness is going to deal with this dark psychic force of the collective eyes hatred that this president is bringing up in this country, then I'm afraid that the Democrats are going to see some very dark days.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Love her or hate her, she's got two things in common with Trump.  She's no politician and she's got a point of view. Just don't ask her about her pet. UNIDENTIFIED REPORTER Do you have a pet?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMSON
utterances.utterance: Do I have a pet? I have a cat, and the cat died.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The cat died. That ain't no politician's answer. But she wasn't the only one with Trump on the brain.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: RYAN
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: STEVE BULLOCK
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS
utterances.utterance: Trump is a pathological liar.

utterances.speaker: O'ROURKE
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: AMY KLOBUCHAR
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: HICKENLOOPER
utterances.utterance: That's how we're going to beat Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: BULLOCK
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMSON
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump disgraces the office of president.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMSON
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: HICKENLOOPER
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: RYAN
utterances.utterance: We've got to get rid of Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: O'ROURKE
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: DELANEY
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump is the symptom of a disease.

utterances.speaker: BUTTIGIEG
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: KLOBUCHAR
utterances.utterance: Let's get real. Tonight, we debate but ultimately we have to beat Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, maybe it's me but all that talk about Trump makes him even more alluring. It's like when dad says stay away from those magazines at the barber shop. You think, hey, let's go check out those magazines at the barber shop. Juan laughed at that. It's weird how ten people talking trash about you makes you seem so much bigger. Yet, Trump loomed over the debate like the devil in the exorcist. Reducing the party to a bunch of possess children helplessly shaking in their beds.  No comfort came from that room, but also no candidate either. Dana, I saw one of your perceptive tweets last night, and you do that thing where you -- I notice not only what was there but what wasn't there. And what wasn't there -- what wasn't mention, Dana?

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Well, first of all, CNN, I praise them for starting the debate at 8 PM, but what wasn't there was the truth that it was three hours long --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- not two hours long. I don't know --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You see there's no mention of impeachment, and no Mueller, no collusion.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah. And also, no send her back.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Send her back was a big -- and no Biden.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No Biden.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like, nobody mentioned any of those things. That, obviously, is not going to be the case tonight when Biden is on the stage. The other thing that you mentioned that Marianne has that Trump had, she also has a following.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: A ready-made following. They've been following her for decades.  It's not the same crowd that followed President Trump through -- if you followed him in New York when he was on The Apprentice who became an international star. Marianne is an international star as well. So I think she's confounding Democrats a little bit because -- like, why does she have all this support? Where is it coming from? She's been building it for years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I also like -- I do like the fact that I understand what she's saying. She's waging a psychological battle, Juan. Like, she's talking about the psyche of the nation, and I think people can understand that.  What did you make of like the family feud last night between the moderates and the not moderates?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: First, you know, I listened to your monologue with such interest, and then I heard about Ms. Cleo.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And I thought to myself, isn't that -- she was the -- was she a black woman on TV?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She was psychic. Wasn't she Ms. Cleo the psychic? The 1-800 number.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, that was it. You could dial 1-800.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes, yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So now, 1-800 you get Marianne.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You get Marianne and -- but I don't know if she gets the White House. But I must say she got lots of attention. I read -- and because this is so alien to me. I read she was the most searched person on the stage last night in terms of googling and the like, right? So I guess people are like, oh, who is she? What's this about? I think some of you know who she is. I really don't know who she is because, politically, she's a nobody. So it's a little-bit of a stunner.  I get the whole Trump analogy (INAUDIBLE) like Trump. But, you know what, at some point, I think, would she fall off the stage for the next round?  Apparently not.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I think she might gone up --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: She has a following.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Was there anybody like -- you thought -- out of the group that you thought was the strongest?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think, clearly, Elizabeth Warren came on the stage as the strongest and left as the strongest. I don't think anybody did any damage to Elizabeth Warren. To me, the whole notion that it's a family feud I think it's healthy. I think that's what we should be seeing. We should be seeing a debate that helps to determine who the candidate. I mean, you look back to 2016. Republicans were far more divided. Lying Ted, Little Marco, low-energy. You think about the wall. There was only one guy up there who said, yeah, the wall is a great idea. Trade, foreign trade, non-intervention -- war in Iraq. Donald Trump didn't tell the truth, but he said that he had opposed the war in Iraq or something.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He kind of did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Directionally told the truth.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know, but I thought that it was a real substantive debate about Medicare for all, about the environment with Delaney playing the foil to Sanders and Warren, making some real good points and forcing them to defend their points. And then when he spoke about the costs --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We'll do that in the B-block.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. Let's do it in --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: B-block. All right, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: You called it a squabble. You called it a feud. I say that it was an intervention. This was the rise of the realist who are trying to rescue the party away from socialism. And Bernie and Warren, they're just lighting themselves on fire right now. This is a big bonfire of socialism. And all these realist were like throwing water -- hey, math, reality, this is going to get us killed in a landslide. But they don't care. They just want to light everything on fire and so the audience. And the audience claps every time some socialist says something crazy --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know why? Because it's popular.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It is -- socialism is popular --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So were cults too in the 70's, Juan. I'm not saying this is going to work. Something popular doesn't mean it's going to be good. But, right now, I think what's happening is, Warren, I disagree. I thought she was frenetic. I thought she was annoying.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Really?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: She failed the commander-in-chief test when she took the first nuke strike option off the table. Like she's going to sacrifice an American city and let North Korea throw a missile over here, and then respond after we lost millions of people. Absolutely crazy. She refused to answer the question about whether she'd raise taxes on the middle class.  And then Bernie gets out there. Bernie is a nothing in Washington his whole career. He only knows how to take. He doesn't know how to create.  And he's just a rage-a-holic. No one was presidential timber. No one had any sense of humor. Marianne Williamson, she's like homeopathic therapy. Everyone's on stage is like Advil and aspirin and bare, and she's like yoga, like CBD oil, and she's -- but she's tapped into some real energy in the country. I just don't think that energy is fully formed yet, but she's got into it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What about you, Emily? What did you -- what were your highlights and low lights?

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Yeah. It's interesting, I agree with part of what you said. To me, it was like a Hunger Games style big fish in a small pond. And the progressives won to me. I think Bernie emerged as the commander, and that he and Elizabeth were clearly the pros on stage, but they failed at that commander level, I agree. I think, to me, it was clear that the progressives won. But at what cost to the party, at what cost to the reality of the moderate faction, which to me was eclipsed. I think that the a-ha moments, and the dramatic moments, and the zingers and quips got all the applause and got all the excitement. But in reality, I think a lot of voters at home were like, wait, I would like, actually, more info from that moderate over there, and I would like more air time from that moderate over there. And so, to me, it was analogy of, once again, CNN taking away the choice from the voter at home --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You couldn't really get full answers because the rules that they had set out had the moderators were forced then to try to -- to cut off everybody just as they were about to make a point --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- they'll cut them off.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I thought two-thirds of the moderators did a really good job. I thought that they must have been cringing with Lemon going -- just editorializing, I thought it was a bit odd. I mean, it's like having me up there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's what Trump said. So Trump went after Lemon, right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And I mean, you know, he's in self-defense mode. But, you know, to me there were two outstanding moments for the Democrats. One, when Elizabeth Warren says to the so-called moderates, I think they're more conservative, hey, why are you running for president just to tell us what we can't do? The other one was Pete -- Mayor Pete saying, oh, you know what? The Republicans are going to call us socialist whether you are liberal or conservative.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Typical socialist.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They're called conservatives now, but the ground has shifted under their feet --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- it's like because the party has moved so far-left, then you ended up -- you end up being called a conservative Democrat.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Did you see who the most tweeted about candidate was, though, by the way. It was still Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: No matter what happened, it was still Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There you go. All right, we've got to move on. We've got another segment. The gloves come off with socialists battling moderates for Medicare for all.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Second of all -- second of all --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I wrote the damn bill.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: More of the heated debate moments, next.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Peter chose that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't know? Peter chose it. OK. The fireworks in Detroit as the debate brawl breaks out over Medicare for all. Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren attacking private health insurance while clashing with moderates over how to pay for their progressive plans. Now, both Warren and Sanders forced to defend their policies last night, watch.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: He has called the idea a political suicide that will just get President Trump re-elected. What do you say to Congressman Delaney?

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (D-VT)
utterances.utterance: You're wrong.

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: When you end up in a hospital in Canada, you come out with no bill at all. Healthcare is a human right, not a privilege. I believe that. I will fight for that.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: But we don't have to go around and be the party of subtraction and telling half the country who has private health insurance that their health insurance is illegal. But why do we got to be the party of taking something away from people.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: No is the party --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: That's what they're running on. They're running on telling half the country that your health insurance is illegal.

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN (D-MA)
utterances.utterance: We are not about trying to take away healthcare from anyone. That's what the Republicans are trying to do. And we should stop using Republican talking points in order to talk with each other about how to best provide that healthcare.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Republican arguments aren't necessarily just talking points, Jesse. But that got pretty heated.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sometimes they're just points.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, the arguments.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: How are you going to pay for it? Are you going to raise taxes?  And how is it going to work? Apparently, that's a partisan talking point.  If Obamacare was so great, why is everyone talking about repealing and replacing Obamacare on a Democrat debate? I mean, this is crazy. I couldn't even understand half of their plans. They don't make any sense at all. Tim Ryan made the best point I think of everybody. These unions have negotiated these amazing healthcare plan, Cadillac plans they're so good.  They have their own name. Why would you rip those away? And not only that, and then give them to illegal immigrants? It makes no sense politically and as a policy, and Warren totally out of touch. I don't know about you guys, but I like my healthcare. I go to the doctor. I check in.  I give a $5 co-pay. He tells me I'm fine. I leave. I do no paperwork.  It's great. And 180 million Americans feel that way. Only 27 million Americans do not have health insurance right now. Let's focus on them instead of tearing the whole system down. And Bernie, he thinks making a profit is evil. I don't know what he's talking about.  So many great things have been done through Aetna, Blue Cross and Blue Shield. I don't think these are evil companies. I think these are good companies that need to bring costs down. And there's ways to do that without destroying a great system. Trump can exploit this divide within the Democratic Party, and it's a gift because the Republicans -- I'm not really sure what their healthcare plan is, but the Democrats are making it so easy to exploit by offering up this socialist utopia that makes no sense and does remove healthcare from a lot of people.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And it felt like, Emily, that Delaney and others were trying to say, look, we know from the researcher out in the field, they're talking to people, you say Medicare for all, kind of popular. As soon as you start saying here's what could happen under it. And that's why I like Bernie Sanders is almost impervious to the consequences of the bill -- the damn bill that he wrote, right? So he's like -- he say I wrote the bill, like, yeah, there are consequence -- you can't say it's free.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Exactly. And I think that's why the momentum behind it stops at the tag line, right? It stops at Medicare for all, and then once you get into the iceberg below it, it's so obvious that as the cost came out today, the $3.2 trillion, it's not worth it. It takes away choice from people.  It ignores the fact that everything has a cost and somewhere it has to be absorbed. So if it's not you absorbing it, then it's a business absorbing it which means that you're fielding the cost later, etcetera. So once -- again, I think it's just that kind of overarching approach that they're taking. And I think it was funny that immediately Bernie's camp would made the sticker, I wrote the damn bill, and he thought it was so amazing. And I think the GOP should make stickers that say 3.2 trillion --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's 32 trillion.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: It's 32 trillion, thank you. Even more as rebuttal. Exactly.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Healthcare we know, Juan, like one of the top issues. People worry -- and mostly about the cost of like hospital care, or unexpected expenses that they are worried would bankrupt them. So you think the Democrats have a plan for that, that's better than Republicans?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, because I think in action is not acceptable, Dana. And the Republicans have no plan. Remember, you had two years with Republicans in control of the House and the Senate and the White House and they did nothing. Jesse is talking about, oh, people don't like Obamacare. The polls show people now more than 50 percent like Obamacare. And guess what?  The Democrats are trying to build on Obamacare. It's only Biden who says he would just stick with Obamacare and built slightly repair its flaws.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: People like their own companies-sponsored health insurance.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, they do. But the key point to me is --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So why do they want to take that away?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: They don't want to take it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, they do. That's the Medicare for all plan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Medicare for all would say that you actually get fewer deductions --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- Fox News sponsored health insurance policy --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Excuse me, let me finish.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- be given to the feds?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm not giving anything.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They manage the whole plan, Juan. It's a government-run plan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And I'm saying I would get more coverage. My taxes would go up.  That's the thing that people are pointing to. And also the argument --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. Here's what I'm thinking to you. Taxes might go up. And secondly, people would say it's a big government plan. Do you really trust big government to deliver for the individual? And on both cases what you hear from Sanders and Warren is, yeah, your taxes might go up, but you would pay less for coverage and all those people --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All those people who have less than adequate coverage would be covered.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Even just looking at the U.K., it's never enough.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: When the Democrats say taxes might go up, that means taxes are going up. OK. I always figure like let's do this to what the left really likes. Like education, the campus. We know Medicare for all will result in doctors being paid less. Hospitals being paid less. Procedures being paid less. Long waiting lines to see specialists and more pressure on a system especially primary care. So let's apply this. Let's do education for all. Not cancelling the debt because that only hurts the banks. But let's say free education for all. That would apply to professors, right?  The left. They would have longer hours, they would have lower pay, they'll have more red tape, and there'd be no funding for all of their precious research because there wouldn't be any money. So if you applied Medicare for all into an area where you can't demonize the person like a doctor, but like, oh, the poor professors, they would run screaming. They'd have their pitchforks if they knew where they could buy them at the hardware store.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So you know what that's called? Public schools. Public schools work.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm talking about universities.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, I'm just saying, that's what we know.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Actually, I love that. I think we should come back to it another day. But for now, Democrat candidates clash over -- guess what? Climate change and a green new deal, of course. The fiery showdown, but we heard it before when we return.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It wouldn't be a Democratic debate without liberal doomsday climate predictions and the green new deal. The candidates rolled out their tired talking points and there was also one big moment everyone is talking about. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Climate crisis is the existential crisis for our world. It puts every living thing on this planet at risk.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: We don't have more than ten years to get this right.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: By 2030, we will have passed the point of no return on climate.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: There is no choice. We have got to be super aggressive.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The green new deal makes sure that every Americans guaranteed a government job if they want. That is a disaster at the ballot box. You might as well FedEx the election to Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Dana, first of all, I thought it was 12 years was the time limit when we had to survive -- I don't know what happened?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: In 1997, when I first worked on the hill, and there was a hearing about this, it was 30 years -- so 12. I think by tonight's debate, it will be five weeks.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Because they have to keep ratcheting it up, up and up.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And I think Al Gore said that in 2014 the earth was going to be decimated. And now it's 2019.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: 2019. Well, here we are. And I think that they've done to themselves a very good service of -- it's hard to do it in a sound bite, OK? To say the world is ending. We've just seen all of these huge fires in the arctic, right? The tundra is melting and the things are happening - - like, it's all happening -- like, they could say it's happening right now. The question is, then what do you do about it? How do you act on it? And Hickenlooper, the governor of Colorado, is basically trying to say you have to be realistic about this.
